commentBody:
@Rich Roberts
X and J are 8.
Q and Z are 10.

@Bill in Yokohama
One side, *and* one edge. Make yourself one, put your finger on the edge, and follow it around. And around. And around. And ...

(After all, the way you make one is to cut a loop, then flip an end to join one edge to the other edge)!

@Grumpy

follow it around, and around and around, and... get a nasty paper cut!

thanks for showing me my error/that CLM was correct

@SP,

Love the idea of the J at the end of a Down answer representing a hook at the end of a line. 

A puzzle theme, perhaps? 🤔

@Rachel
"Extremely rare"? No. I've seen it spelled ghanouj plenty of times, in restaurants and cookbooks. Also ganouj. I was trying (unsuccessfully) to solve with only the across clues, and that was the first theme answer I got. 

I liked the theme, simply because ending entries with a J is thinking outside the box. I mean how many puzzles have you seen with SASS filling in the last across row?

@jennie
With you on 55D. I can think of a dozen better clues, although I did like AMOS and VAMOS  buddying it up, along with Xlandia solid citizens AFAR and AJAR. 

I also enjoyed the workout provided by LACE UP, MARINER, FAST BREAK, DART, DUNK, POP, and JUMP ON IT. Whew!

@SBK
They were saying to sing the lyric to the tune of Lady Marmalade, not implying that the lyric was IN Lady Marmalade.

Kind of like when I change the lyrics of a song so they're about my cat.

@Times Rita

Please, don't get me started on English spelling again 😄

That being said, transcription from other languages is never easy. However you spell it is fine (-ish?) as long as the pronunciation approximates the original.

@Xword Junkie
BABA GHANOUJ is a perfectly cromulent spelling. I've seen it spelled with both the J and the SH. It's by no means an obscure variant.

And as someone who's worked in broadcast for fifteen years, I can assure you that RADIO DJ is very much a thing. (I would think the J TILE in Scrabble would be a gimme for crossword fans.)

@Xword Junkie

Since RADIO DJ was a themer, that should  have been a gimme.  

And since it's hard to argue that there's a "standard" way to spell BABA GHANOUJ, one might say that all its spellings are variants.

@Katie

Yes, I've seen the spelling BABAGHANOUJ occasionally. I never called it "obscure". It is a "variant", with the most common spelling likely being BABAGHANOUSH.

Of course a RADIODJ is a "thing". And, of course, JTILE was a gimme for me. Still, the pairing JTILE/RADIODJ felt especially contrived to me thematically. FRESHOJ did too in a way---even though I've drunk it many times. ;-)

@Mary and Kosta in France
Prostete. Dali razbiraš makedonski?

(Yes, I did look it up!)

@B

I don't know if this would work with the device you solve on, but I keep xwordinfo.com open in a tab so I can go over to check references in the comments.

It's still annoying, but at least it wouldn't ruin your stats.

@B

I have emailed SO many times about the broken timer, all for the verbal equivalent of a pat on the shoulder in response. I don't play for time, but returning to a puzzle that is many many *hours* longer than it should be is an incredibly deflating experience. 

Sigh.

@The X-Phile
It happens more often than you'd think.

There are still old-school DJs out there who dig out 45s to play on-air. In Minneapolis, Q Bear of KMOJ sometimes plays old records in the afternoon drive. There's only hits in the crates!

@Joe

I remember Conried from the game show Charades.

A common ploy was to have a full Shakespearean soliloquy as the subject.  When one or two key words were found, he would reel off the full page. That made an impression on me.  Professional actors know their stuff.

@Mishlev
Wasn't that a U2 song? 
"Where the streets have no J."

@Mishlev

Thanks, that helps explain Ioan as an equivalent of John.

Interesting tier J came so late when there are so many variants of Jon Jean Jhon Jen Jennifer Jill Jonathan Jerry Jack etc. etc.

@JohnWM

It happens rarely during play.  Usually the result of getting stepped on or shoe malfunction, (sole separation and such).

I believe the clue was the pre-game routine of lacing up ice skates before going out onto the rink.

@Mortiser

Tomato, tomato.

:)

@Joe P SNARF is my enemy! 😂 It's been in the puzzle several times lately, and I never learn. Every time, I write down a hopeful ScARF. Every time, they dash my dreams.

SNARF just feels like the wronger answer to me. I know the word, but at least for my dialect it's much more obscure than ScARF. I'd use it more to describe how an animal eats than a person. 

(My feelings on SNARFing aside, this was a cute puzzle)
